Definition 5.2 (Subcomplexes of cell functors). Let $F$ be a presented cell functor (as in Definition 4.5). A subcomplex $C$ of $F$ is a subset of the set of cells of $F$ that for each $i\geq 1$ satisfies the following inductive condition: $P_{i}$ Suppose that as a result of the condition $P_{i-1}$ we have constructed a functor $C_{i-1}$ and a monomorphism $C_{i-1}\to F_{i-1}$ (where $C_{0}=*$). The condition $P_{i}$ is then that for each cell $\alpha$ of degree $i$ in $C$, the attaching map for $\alpha$ of the form $I^{\alpha}_{0}\wedge\mathcal{C}(K_{\alpha},-)\to F_{i-1}$ factors via $C_{i-1}\to F_{i-1}$. (Such a factorization is unique because $C_{i-1}\to F_{i-1}$ is a monomorphism.) With this condition satisfied, we define $C_{i}$ by the pushout diagram $\diagram\node{\bigvee_{\alpha}I^{\alpha}_{0}\wedge\mathcal{C}(K_{\alpha},-)}% \arrow{e}\arrow{s}\node{C_{i-1}}\arrow{s}\\ \node{\bigvee_{\alpha}I^{\alpha}_{1}\wedge\mathcal{C}(K_{\alpha},-)}\arrow{e}% \node{C_{i}}$ with the map $C_{i}\to F_{i}$ then determined by the universal property of the pushout and the diagrams that define the cell structure on $F$. The map $C_{i}\to F_{i}$ constructed in this way is a relative cell functor and hence a monomorphism by Lemma 5.1. The data associated to the subcomplex $C$ (that is, the sequence $*=C_{0}\to C_{1}\to\dots$ and the pushout diagrams above) form a presented cell functor in their own right. We abuse notation by writing $C$ for this functor, that is, for the colimit of the sequence of $C_{i}$. The colimit of the maps $C_{i}\to F_{i}$ is then a map $C\to F$ which we call the inclusion of the subcomplex $C$ into $F$.
Definition 9.17 (Bar resolutions). Let $P$ be a reduced operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ and let $R$ be a right $P$-module. We define a map $B(R,P,P)\to R$ of symmetric sequences as follows. Treating $R$ as a constant simplicial object we define maps $B_{\bullet}(R,P,P)\to R$ by means of the iterated composition maps $R\circ P^{k}\circ P\to R\circ P\to R.$ These commute with the face and degeneracies and so taking realizations, we get the required map $B(R,P,P)\to R.$ Similarly, if $L$ is a left $P$-module, we obtain a map of symmetric sequences of the form $B(P,P,L)\to L.$ If $M$ is a $P$-bimodule, there is a corresponding map $B(P,P,M,P,P)\to M.$
Definition 17.6. Let $F:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be a presented cell functor. Then we have a natural map $r:F\Omega^{\infty}\to F\Omega^{\infty}\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}$ given by the unit of the adjunction between $\Sigma^{\infty}$ and $\Omega^{\infty}$ that makes $F\Omega^{\infty}$ into a right comodule over the comonad $\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}$. Now $F\Omega^{\infty}$ is also a presented cell functor (by Lemma 17.1). Therefore, by Proposition 17.5, we have a map $r^{*}:\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})\circ\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{% \infty})\to\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})$ that makes $\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})$ into a pro-right-$\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})$-module. We now form the homotopically correct bar construction for the pro-module $\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})$: $\partial^{*}(F):=B(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty}),\tilde{\partial}^{*}% (\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}),\mathsf{1}).$ This is a pro-right-comodule over the cooperad $B(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}))$.
Definition 1.7 (Cell complexes). A relative cell complex in either $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ or $\mathsf{Spec}$ is a map that can be expressed as the composite of a countable sequence of pushouts along coproducts of the generating cofibrations. A cell complex is an object $X$ such that $*\to X$ is a relative cell complex. We refer to Hirschhorn’s book [22, §10] for the general theory of cell complexes. We refer to cell complexes in $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ just as cell complexes, and cell complexes in $\mathsf{Spec}$ as cell spectra. This definition of cell spectra agrees with that given in [13, III.2] (except that they call them ‘cell $S$-modules’). A cell complex or cell spectrum is finite if it has a cell structure with finitely many cells. For each of the categories $\mathcal{C}=\mathsf{sSet}_{*},\mathsf{Spec}$, let $\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}$ denote the full subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ whose objects are the finite cell complexes. In each of these cases, $\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}$ is a skeletally small category that inherits a simplicial enrichment from $\mathcal{C}$ with the same simplicial mapping objects $\mathcal{C}(X,Y)$. We say that an object in $\mathcal{C}$ is homotopy-finite if it is weakly equivalent (i.e. connected by a zigzag of weak equivalences) to an object in $\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}$.
Definition 1.24 (Functors). We are interested in studying functors between the categories $\mathsf{Spec}$ and $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$. To make the technical constructions of this paper, we need some basic conditions on such functors. Let $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ be a functor where $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ are each either $\mathsf{Spec}$ or $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$. Then we say • $F$ is pointed if $F(*)=*$; • $F$ is simplicial if it induces maps of simplicial sets of the form $\mathcal{C}(X,Y)\to\mathcal{D}(FX,FY)$ where recall that $\mathcal{C}(X,Y)$ denotes the simplicial set of maps from $X$ to $Y$ in the category $\mathcal{C}$. Notice that a simplicial functor $F$ is pointed if and only if all these are maps of pointed simplicial sets, that is, preserve the basepoint. • $F$ is a homotopy functor if it preserves weak equivalences, that is if $X\;\tilde{\longrightarrow}\;Y$ is a weak equivalence in $\mathcal{C}$, then $FX\;\tilde{\longrightarrow}\;FY$ is a weak equivalence in $\mathcal{D}$ • $F$ is finitary if it preserves filtered homotopy colimits in the following sense: given a filtered diagram $X:\mathcal{I}\to\mathcal{C}$, the natural map $\operatorname*{hocolim}_{i\in\mathcal{I}}F(X(i))\to F\left(\operatorname*{% hocolim}_{i\in\mathcal{I}}X(i)\right),$ should be a weak equivalence. Strictly speaking the map involved in the definition of when $F$ is finitary is a zigzag involving inverse weak equivalences. We therefore really mean that each of the forward maps involved in that zigzag should be also be a weak equivalence.
Definition 11.13 (Bar constructions for pro-modules). Let $P$ be an operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$, let $R$ be a pro-right-$P$-module (indexed over $\mathcal{J}$) and $L$ a pro-left-$P$-module (indexed over $\mathcal{K}$). We can then form the two-sided bar construction $B(R,P,L)$. This is the pro-symmetric sequence indexed over the cofiltered category $\mathcal{J}\times\mathcal{K}$ given by $B(R,P,L)_{(j,k)}:=B(R_{j},P,L_{k}).$ Note that this could also be defined as the realization of a simplicial bar construction based on the composition product for pro-symmetric sequences (see Definition 11.7). We can treat the unit symmetric sequence as a pro-object indexed over the trivial category. We then have a one-sided bar construction $B(R,P,\mathsf{1})$ indexed over $\mathcal{J}$ and given by $B(R,P,\mathsf{1})_{j}:=B(R_{j},P,\mathsf{1}).$ This is clearly a pro-right-$BP$-comodule. We also have $B(\mathsf{1},P,L)$ indexed over $\mathcal{K}$ given by $B(\mathsf{1},P,L)_{k}:=B(\mathsf{1},P,L_{k}).$ This is a pro-left-$BP$-comodule. If in addition $M$ is a pro-$P$-bimodule indexed on the category $\mathcal{L}$, then we can form the bimodule bar construction $B(R,P,M,P,L)$. This is a pro-symmetric sequence indexed on $\mathcal{J}\times\mathcal{L}\times\mathcal{K}$ given by $B(R,P,M,P,L)_{(j,l,k)}:=B(R_{j},P,M_{l},P,L_{k}).$ In particular, we have a pro-$BP$-comodule $B(\mathsf{1},P,M,P,\mathsf{1})$ indexed on $\mathcal{L}$.
Definition 6.3 (Properties of pro-objects). A pro-object $X$ in the category $\mathcal{C}$ is said to have a property levelwise if there is some pro-object $Y$, isomorphic to $X$, such that each $Y_{j}$ has that property. A map $\phi:X\to Y$ of pro-objects has a property levelwise if there exists a level representation $\phi^{\prime}$ of $\phi$ such that each map $\phi^{\prime}_{j}$ has that property.
Definition 10.3 (Mapping objects for modules). Let $P$ be an operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ and let $R,R^{\prime}$ be right $P$-modules. We then define a spectrum $\operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(R,R^{\prime}):=\lim\left(\operatorname% {Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(R,R^{\prime})\rightrightarrows\operatorname{Map}_{% \mathsf{\Sigma}}(R\circ P,R^{\prime})\right)$ where one of the arrows on the right-hand side is induced by the module structure map $R\circ P\to R$, and the other is the composite $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(R,R^{\prime})\to\operatorname{Map}_{% \mathsf{\Sigma}}(R\circ P,R^{\prime}\circ P)\to\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{% \Sigma}}(R\circ P,R^{\prime})$ where the first map here comes from Definition 10.2, and the second is induced by the module structure map $R^{\prime}\circ P\to R^{\prime}$. This gives us an enrichment of $\mathsf{Mod}_{\mathsf{right}}(P)$ over $\mathsf{Spec}$ and we get a corresponding simplicial enrichment by replacing $\operatorname{Map}_{\Sigma}(-,-)$ with $\operatorname{Hom}_{\Sigma}(-,-)$. If $L$ and $L^{\prime}$ are left $P$-modules, we define $\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(L,L^{\prime}):=\lim\left(\operatorname{% Hom}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(L,L^{\prime})\rightrightarrows\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathsf{\Sigma}}(P\circ L,L^{\prime})\right)$ in the corresponding way. Similarly, if $M$ and $M^{\prime}$ are $P$-bimodules, we define $\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M,M^{\prime}):=\lim\left(\operatorname{% Hom}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,M^{\prime})\rightrightarrows\operatorname{Hom}_{% \mathsf{\Sigma}}(P\circ M\circ P,M^{\prime})\right).$ Note that $\operatorname{Hom}_{P}(L,L^{\prime})$ and $\operatorname{Hom}_{P}(M,M^{\prime})$ are only simplicial sets. There are no natural enrichments for left and bi- $P$-modules over $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 17.14. Now let $F:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be a presented cell functor. Recall from Definition 17.6 that $\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})$ is a right module over the operad $\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})$. Also recall the definition of $\operatorname{Ext}$-objects for pro-right-$P$-modules from Definition 11.18. We then make the following definition: $\Phi_{n}(F)(X):=\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{right}}_{\tilde{\partial}^{*}(% \Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})}\left(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty}),(% \Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\leq n}\right).$ Recall that the $\operatorname{Ext}$-objects for right $P$-modules are formed in $\mathsf{Spec}$. Hence $\Phi_{n}(F)$ is a functor from $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ to $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 8.3 (Induced maps on bar constructions). Now suppose that $f:P\to P^{\prime}$ is a morphism of reduced operads, $r:R\to R^{\prime}$ a morphism that respects right module structures on $R$ and $R^{\prime}$ via $f$, and $l:L\to L^{\prime}$ a morphism that respects left module structures on $L$ and $L^{\prime}$ via $f$. Then the triple $(r,f,l)$ induces a morphism of symmetric sequences $(r,f,l)_{*}:B(R,P,L)\to B(R^{\prime},P^{\prime},L^{\prime})$ via the induced maps $r\circ f^{k}\circ l:R\circ P^{k}\circ L$. In particular, $f$ induces a morphism $f_{*}:B(P)\to B(P^{\prime}).$ If $P^{\prime}=P$ and $f$ is the identity map, then $r:R\to R^{\prime}$ is just a morphism of right $P$-modules, and induces a map $r_{*}:B(R,P,\mathsf{1})\to B(R^{\prime},P,\mathsf{1}).$ Similarly, $l:L\to L^{\prime}$ is a morphism of left $P$-modules and induces a map $l_{*}:B(\mathsf{1},P,L)\to B(\mathsf{1},P,L^{\prime}).$
Definition 2.1 (Cartesian and cocartesian cubes). Recall that a cubical diagram of simplicial sets or spectra is cartesian if the map from the initial vertex to the homotopy limit of the remaining diagram is an equivalence, and cocartesian if the map to the terminal vertex from the homotopy colimit of the remaining diagram is an equivalence. Such a cubical diagram is strongly cocartesian if every two-dimensional face is cocartesian.
Definition 12.4 (Models for the derivatives of functors of spectra). Let $F:{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{fin}}}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be a presented cell functor and $n$ a positive integer. Define a pro-spectrum $\partial^{n}(F)$, indexed on the cofiltered category $\mathsf{Sub}(F)^{op}$, by the formula $\partial^{n}(F):=\{\operatorname{Nat}(CX,X^{\wedge n})\}_{C\in\mathsf{Sub}(F)}.$ The pro-object $\partial^{n}(F)$ has a $\Sigma_{n}$-action that arises from the permutation action of $\Sigma_{n}$ on $X^{\wedge n}$. Together these pro-objects form a pro-symmetric sequence $\partial^{*}(F)$ with $n$th term equal to $\partial^{n}(F)$.
Definition 7.12 (Cooperads and comodules). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a symmetric monoidal category. Then the opposite category $\mathcal{C}^{op}$ has a natural symmetric monoidal structure given by that of $\mathcal{C}$. Also a symmetric sequence in $\mathcal{C}$ can be identified with a symmetric sequence in $\mathcal{C}^{op}$ via the isomorphism of categories $\mathsf{\Sigma}\cong\mathsf{\Sigma}^{op}$ that sends a bijection to its inverse. We then define a cooperad in $\mathcal{C}$ to be an operad in the symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{C}^{op}$, but viewed as a symmetric sequence in $\mathcal{C}$ rather than $\mathcal{C}^{op}$. Thus a cooperad in $\mathcal{C}$ is a symmetric sequence together with structure maps of the form $Q(n_{1}+\dots+n_{k})\to Q(k)\wedge Q(n_{1})\wedge\dots\wedge Q(n_{k}).$ The opposite of a closed symmetric monoidal category is very rarely closed so we are relying on the traditional definition (Remark 7.9) to say what an operad in $\mathcal{C}^{op}$ is. If $Q$ is a cooperad in $\mathcal{C}$, we write $Q^{op}$ for the corresponding operad in $\mathcal{C}^{op}$. It is useful to have notation for the dual of the composition product. We write $M\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}N$ for the composition product of the symmetric sequences $M$ and $N$ viewed as symmetric sequences in $\mathcal{C}^{op}$. The object $(M\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}N)(n)$ is then just the product (rather than the coproduct) of the same terms used to define $(M\circ N)(n)$. With this notation, a cooperad consists of a symmetric sequence $Q$ and a map $Q\to Q\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}Q$ satisfying certain axioms dual to those for operads. Note that the operation $\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}$ is unlikely to be associative, again since $\mathcal{C}^{op}$ is usually not closed symmetric monoidal. If $Q$ is a cooperad in $\mathcal{C}$, then a right $Q$-comodule is a right $Q^{op}$-module considered as a symmetric sequence in $\mathcal{C}$, i.e. it consists of a symmetric sequence $R$ and a right $Q$-coaction $R\to R\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}Q$. A left $Q$-comodule is a left $Q^{op}$-module, so consists of a symmetric sequence $L$ and a left $Q$-coaction $L\to Q\mathbin{\hat{\circ}}L$. A $Q$-bicomodule is a $Q^{op}$-bimodule. As with operads and modules there are obvious notions of morphisms of cooperads and comodules and we obtain corresponding categories.
Definition 18.10. For a presented cell functor $F:\mathsf{Spec}\to\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$, we now construct a map $\phi:F\to\Phi_{n}(F)$ along similar lines to the map $\phi$ of Definition 17.20.If $F$ is a finite cell functor, we define $\phi^{\prime}_{F}(n):F(X)\wedge\partial^{n}(\Sigma^{\infty}F)\to\operatorname{% Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge n})$ that are adjoint to the natural evaluation $\Sigma^{\infty}F(X)\wedge\operatorname{Nat}(\Sigma^{\infty}F(X),X^{\wedge n})% \to X^{\wedge n}.$ The maps $\phi^{\prime}_{F}(n)$ are $\Sigma_{n}$-equivariant and so together they determine a map $\phi^{\prime}_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(\partial^{*}(% \Sigma^{\infty}F),\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*})).$ Now the symmetric sequences on the right-hand side here are left $\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})$-modules, and we claim that the above map factors via the mapping object for left modules on the right-hand side in place of the mapping object for symmetric sequences. This is equivalent to showing that the following diagram commutes: $\diagram\node{F(X)\wedge\partial^{k}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})\wedge% \partial^{n_{1}}(\Sigma^{\infty}F)\wedge\dots\wedge\partial^{n_{k}}(\Sigma^{% \infty}F)}\arrow{e}\arrow{s,r}{(\phi^{\prime}_{F}(n_{1})\wedge\dots\wedge\phi_% {F}(n_{r}))\circ\Delta_{F(X)}}\node{F(X)\wedge\partial^{n_{1}+\dots+n_{k}}(% \Sigma^{\infty}F)}\arrow{s,r}{\phi^{\prime}_{F}(n_{1}+\dots+n_{k})}\\ \node{\partial^{k}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{% c},X^{\wedge n_{1}})\wedge\dots\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge n_{k}}% )}\arrow{e}\node{\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge(n_{1}+\dots+n_{k})})}$ The left vertical map comes from combining the diagonal on the pointed simplicial set $C(X)$ with the maps $\beta_{C}(n_{1}),\dots,\beta_{C}(n_{k})$. The top horizontal map is the module structure on $\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}C)$, and the bottom horizontal map is the module structure on $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*})$. Making use of various adjunctions, the commutativity of the above diagram is implied by that of $\diagram\node{\Sigma^{\infty}F(X)\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{\wedge k% })}\arrow{e}\arrow{s,l}{\Delta_{F(X)}}\node{\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}% \Sigma^{\infty}F(X)\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{\wedge k})}\arrow{s}% \\ \node{\Sigma^{\infty}(F(X)^{\wedge k})\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{% \wedge k})}\arrow{e}\node{(\Sigma^{\infty}F(X))^{\wedge k}}$ Here the top map comes from the $(\Sigma^{\infty},\Omega^{\infty})$-adjunction, the left vertical map from the diagonal on $F(X)$, the bottom map from identifying $\Sigma^{\infty}F(X)$ with $S_{c}\wedge F(X)$, and the right vertical map from the Yoneda isomorphism $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{\wedge k})\cong\operatorname{Nat}(\Sigma^{% \infty}\Omega^{\infty}E,E^{\wedge k}).$ The commutativity of this diagram is given by Lemma 17.12. We therefore obtain a natural (in both $X$ and $F$) transformation $\phi^{\prime\prime}_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{left}}_{\tilde{% \partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})}\left(\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{% \infty}F),\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*})\right).$ Composing with the cofibrant replacement map $\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}F)\to\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}F),$ the truncation map $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*})\to\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\leq n}),$ and the map from $\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}$ to $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}$ of Definition 10.10, we get a natural transformation $\phi_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{left}}_{\tilde{\partial}^{*}(% \Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})}\left(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}F),% \operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\leq n})\right).$ Now for general $F:\mathsf{Spec}\to\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$, we take the homotopy colimit of $\phi_{C}$ over $C\in\mathsf{Sub}(QF)$ and get $\phi:F\to\Phi_{n}(F).$
Definition 11.6 (Spanier-Whitehead duality for pro-symmetric sequences). Let $M$ be a directly-dualizable pro-symmetric sequence indexed on the cofiltered poset $\mathcal{J}$. We define the Spanier-Whitehead dual of $M$ to be the symmetric sequence of spectra given by $(\mathbb{D}M)(n):=\mathbb{D}M(n)$ where $\mathbb{D}M(n)$ is the Spanier-Whitehead dual of the pro-spectrum $M(n)$ as described in Definition 6.11. Explicitly, then we have $(\mathbb{D}M)(n):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in\mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{% Map}(M_{j}(n),S).$ We also write this as $\mathbb{D}M:=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in\mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Map}(% M_{j},S)$ with the understanding that homotopy colimits of diagrams of symmetric sequences are formed termwise.
Definition 4.6 (Cofibrant replacements for functors). Given $F\in[\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}},\mathcal{D}]$, the small object argument determines a cofibrant replacement for $F$, which we write $QF$. The functor $QF$ comes with a canonical cell structure in which the cells of degree $i+1$ are in 1-1 correspondence with commutative diagrams of the form $\diagram\node{I_{0}\wedge\mathcal{C}(K,-)}\arrow{e}\arrow{s}\node{(QF)_{i}}% \arrow{s}\\ \node{I_{1}\wedge\mathcal{C}(K,-)}\arrow{e}\node{F}$ The approximation map $QF\to F$ is always a fibration and a weak equivalence in $[\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}},\mathcal{D}]$, that is, $QF(X)\to F(X)$ is a fibration and a weak equivalence for all $X\in\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}$.
Definition 9.7 (Generating cofibrations for operads and modules). Write $\mathbb{I}$ for the set of generating cofibrations in $\mathsf{Spec}$ (see Definition 1.2). Then we define the following sets of morphisms: • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{\Sigma}}}:=\left\{A_{n}(I_{0})\to A_{n}(I_{% 1})\;|\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 1\right\}$; • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{\Sigma}}_{\mathsf{red}}}:=\left\{A_{n}(I_{0% })\to A_{n}(I_{1})\;|\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 2\right\}$; • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Op}(\mathsf{Spec})}:=\left\{F_{n}(I_{0})\to F_{n}(I_{1})\;% |\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 2\right\}$; • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Mod}_{\mathsf{right}}(P)}:=\left\{R_{n}(I_{0})\to R_{n}(I_% {1})\;|\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 1\right\}$; • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Mod}_{\mathsf{left}}(P)}:=\left\{L_{n}(I_{0})\to L_{n}(I_{% 1})\;|\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 1\right\}$; • $\mathbb{I}_{\mathsf{Mod}_{\mathsf{bi}}(P)}:=\left\{M_{n}(I_{0})\to M_{n}(I_{1}% )\;|\;I_{0}\to I_{1}\in\mathbb{I},\;n\geq 1\right\}$. Similarly, if $\mathbb{J}$ is the set of generating trivial cofibrations in $\mathsf{Spec}$, we define corresponding sets $\mathbb{J}_{\mathcal{C}}$ of morphisms in each of the categories $\mathcal{C}$.
Definition 15.6 (Commutative operad). The commutative operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ is the operad $\mathsf{Com}$ given by $\mathsf{Com}(n):=S$ for all $n$, with the trivial $\Sigma_{n}$-action, and with composition maps given by the unit isomorphisms $S\wedge S\wedge\dots\wedge S\arrow{e,t}{\cong}S$ for the symmetric monoidal structure on $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 6.12 (Spanier-Whitehead dual of a map). Let $f:X\to Y$ be a morphism of pro-spectra with $X$ and $Y$ directly-dualizable as in Definition 6.11. Then $f$ induces a morphism of spectra $\mathbb{D}f:\mathbb{D}Y\to\mathbb{D}X$ in the following way. Recall that $f$ consists of maps $X_{f(j)}\to Y_{j}$ where $f:\mathcal{J}\to\mathcal{I}$ is a map from the indexing category of $Y$ to the indexing category of $X$. We then obtain dual maps $\operatorname{Map}(Y_{j},S)\to\operatorname{Map}(X_{f(j)},S)$ which together make up the required map $\mathbb{D}f:\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in\mathcal{J}}\operatorname{Map}(Y_{j},% S)\to\operatorname*{hocolim}_{i\in\mathcal{I}}\operatorname{Map}(X_{i},S).$ This construction makes $\mathbb{D}$ into a contravariant functor from the full subcategory of $\mathsf{Pro}(\mathsf{Spec})$ consisting of the directly-dualizable spectra, to $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 1.12 (Geometric realization and totalization). If $\mathcal{C}$ is either $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ or $\mathsf{Spec}$, then a simplicial object $X_{\bullet}$ has a geometric realization, written $|X_{\bullet}|$, and a cosimplicial object $X^{\bullet}$ has a totalization, written $\operatorname{Tot}X^{\bullet}$. These can be defined as the following coend and end respectively: $|X_{\bullet}|:=\Delta[n]_{+}\wedge_{\mathsf{\Delta}}X_{n},\quad\operatorname{% Tot}X^{\bullet}:=\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Delta}}(\Delta[n]_{+},X^{n}).$
Definition 18.4. For any $X\in\mathsf{Spec}$, we define a left $\partial^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})$-module structure on the symmetric sequence $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*}).$ Recall that $\partial^{n}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})\cong\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c% }^{\wedge n})$. The left module structure maps are then of the form $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{\wedge k})\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{% \wedge n_{1}})\wedge\dots\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge n_{k}})\to% \operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge(n_{1}+\dots+n_{k})})$ and are given by smashing together terms of the form $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge n_{i}})$ to get $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},S_{c}^{\wedge k})\wedge\operatorname{Map}(S_{c}^{% \wedge k},X^{\wedge(n_{1}+\dots+n_{k})})$ and then using the usual composition of mapping objects. The truncation $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\leq n})$ of this symmetric sequence (see Definition 17.13) then inherits a left module structure and there is a natural map of left modules: $\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\wedge*})\to\operatorname{Map}(S_{c},X^{\leq n}).$
Definition 7.8 (Operads). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a pointed closed symmetric monoidal category. An operad in $\mathcal{C}$ is a monoid for the composition product. In other words, an operad consists of a symmetric sequence $P$ together with a composition map $P\circ P\to P$ and a unit map $\mathsf{1}\to P$ satisfying standard associativity and unit axioms. A morphism of operads is a map of symmetric sequences that commutes with the operad structures.
Definition 1.1 (Simplicial sets). Let $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ be the category of pointed simplicial sets. We denote the simplicial version of the standard $n$-simplex by $\Delta[n]$, and we write $\Delta[n]_{+}$ for this with a disjoint basepoint added. Then $\partial\Delta[n]_{+}$ denotes the simplicial $(n-1)$-sphere with a disjoint basepoint. The category $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ has the following properties: • $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ is a closed symmetric monoidal category with respect to the smash product $\wedge$, with unit object $\Delta[0]_{+}$. We write $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}(X,Y)$ for the internal mapping object; • $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ has a cofibrantly generated pointed proper simplicial monoidal model structure with generating cofibrations given by the inclusions $\partial\Delta[n]_{+}\to\Delta[n]_{+}$ for $n\geq 0$. • Every object of $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ is cofibrant in this model structure.
Definition 9.6 (Free operads and modules on a spectrum). Now let $X$ be a spectrum again. We define the free reduced operad on $X$ in position $n$ by: $F_{n}(X):=F(A_{n}(X))$ for $n\geq 2$, the free right $P$-module on $X$ in position $n$ by: $R_{n}(X):=R(A_{n}(X)),$ the free left $P$-module on $X$ in position $n$ by: $L_{n}(X):=L(A_{n}(X))$ and the free $P$-bimodule on $X$ in position $n$ by: $M_{n}(X):=M(A_{n}(X)).$ These constructions give functors from $\mathsf{Spec}$ to our categories of reduced operads and modules that are left adjoint to the functors that pick out the $n$th term (and forget the $\Sigma_{n}$-action).
Definition 15.1. A comonad on $\mathsf{Spec}$ is a functor $T:\mathsf{Spec}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ together with natural transformations $m:T\to TT,\quad e:T\to I_{\mathsf{Spec}}$ such that the following diagrams commute $\diagram\node{T}\arrow{e,t}{m}\arrow{s,l}{m}\node{TT}\arrow{s,r}{Tm}\\ \node{TT}\arrow{e,t}{mT}\node{TTT},\quad\diagram\node{T}\arrow{e,t}{m}\arrow{% se,b}{1_{T}}\node{TT}\arrow{s,r}{Te}\\ \node[2]{T},\quad\diagram\node{T}\arrow{e,t}{m}\arrow{se,b}{1_{T}}\node{TT}% \arrow{s,r}{eT}\\ \node[2]{T}$
Definition 1.4 (Suspension spectrum and infinite loop-space functors). We warn the reader that the functors $\Sigma^{\infty}$ and $\Omega^{\infty}$ do not have the same meaning in this paper as in [13]. In particular, we define them to be the following functors between $\mathsf{Spec}$ and $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$: • Define $\Sigma^{\infty}:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ by $\Sigma^{\infty}(K):=S_{c}\wedge K$ where here $\wedge$ denotes the tensoring of $\mathsf{Spec}$ over $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$, and $S_{c}$ is as in Definition 1.3. • Define $\Omega^{\infty}:\mathsf{Spec}\to\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ by $\Omega^{\infty}(E):=\mathsf{Spec}(S_{c},E)$ where $\mathsf{Spec}(-,-)$ is the simplicial enrichment of the category $\mathsf{Spec}$. The suspension spectrum and infinite loop-space functors are defined in [13] by $S\wedge K$ and $\mathsf{Spec}(S,E)$ respectively. We use $S_{c}$ because it gives these functors better homotopical properties for our purposes.
Definition 10.1 (Mapping objects). Let $M$ and $N$ be symmetric sequences of spectra. We define $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,N):=\prod_{r=1}^{\infty}\operatorname{% Map}(M(r),N(r))^{\Sigma_{r}}$ where the $\Sigma_{r}$-fixed point object can be defined as the limit of the corresponding $\Sigma_{r}$-indexed diagram in $\mathsf{Spec}$. Equivalently, this is the ‘end’ (in the sense of MacLane [35, IX.5]) of the bifunctor $\mathsf{\Sigma}\times\mathsf{\Sigma}^{op}\to\mathsf{Spec};(r,s)\mapsto% \operatorname{Map}(M(r),N(s)).$ This definition produces an enrichment of the category of symmetric sequences over $\mathsf{Spec}$. There is a corresponding enrichment over $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ which we write $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,N):=\prod_{r=1}^{\infty}\mathsf{Spec}(M% (r),N(r))^{\Sigma_{r}}.$ These are related by $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,N)\cong\mathsf{Spec}(S,\operatorname{% Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,N)).$ This is the same as the simplicial enrichment considered in the proof of Theorem 9.8 (see the appendix).
Definition 17.9. Let $X$ be a pointed simplicial set. Define maps $\Delta_{r}:\Sigma^{\infty}X\wedge\partial^{r}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})% \to(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge r}$ by composing the unit map $\Sigma^{\infty}X\to\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}\Sigma^{\infty}X$ with the evaluation map $\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}\Sigma^{\infty}X\wedge\operatorname{Nat}(\Sigma^% {\infty}\Omega^{\infty}E,E^{\wedge k})\to(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge k}.$ Smashing together these maps appropriately, we get $\Delta_{r_{1},\dots,r_{k}}:(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge k}\wedge\partial^{r_{1}}% (\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})\wedge\dots\wedge\partial^{r^{k}}(\Sigma^{% \infty}\Omega^{\infty})\to(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge(r_{1}+\dots+r_{k})}.$
Definition 8.1 (Weak equivalences). Let $f:A\to B$ be a morphism of symmetric sequences of spectra. We say that $f$ is a weak equivalence if the map $f_{n}:A(n)\to B(n)$ is a weak equivalence in the category $\mathsf{Spec}$ for all $n\geq 1$. A morphism of operads, modules, cooperads or comodules is said to be a weak equivalence if the underlying map of symmetric sequences is a weak equivalence.
Definition A.6. A diagram of the form $A\rightrightarrows B\to C$ is a reflexive coequalizer if it is a coequalizer diagram and the two maps from $A$ to $B$ have a common right inverse.
Definition 11.18 (Mapping objects for pro-modules). Let $M$ be a pro-symmetric sequence, or pro-$P$-module (left-, right- or bi-) for some fixed reduced operad $P$ in $\mathsf{Spec}$. Let $N$ be a (non-pro-) symmetric sequence or $P$-module respectively. Suppose that $M$ is directly-dualizable and is indexed on the cofiltered poset $\mathcal{J}$. We then define $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}(M_{j},N)$ $\operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(M_{j},N)$ $\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(M_{j},N)$ $\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Hom}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M_{j},N)$ accordingly. Similarly, in the module cases, we define $\operatorname{Ext}$-objects: $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(M_{j},N)\cong% \operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(B(M,P,P),N)$ $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(M_{j},N)\cong% \operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(B(P,P,M),N)$ $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M,N):=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in% \mathcal{J}^{op}}\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M_{j},N)\cong% \operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(B(P,P,M,P,P),N)$
Definition 6.6 (Spanier-Whitehead duals). A Spanier-Whitehead dual of a pro-spectrum $X$ is an object $\mathbb{D}X$ in $\mathsf{Spec}$ that corresponds to $X\in\mathsf{Pro}(\mathsf{Spec})$ under the Quillen equivalences of Theorem 6.5. Note that this dual is only defined up to weak equivalence, although a natural (but not canonical) choice can be made by fixing cofibrant replacement functors in the categories of pro- and ind-spectra.
Definition 10.7 (Ext-objects). Let $P$ be a reduced operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ and let $R,R^{\prime}$ be right $P$-modules and suppose that $R$ is $\Sigma$-cofibrant. We define $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(R,R^{\prime}):=\operatorname{Map}^{% \mathsf{right}}_{P}(B(R,P,P),R^{\prime}).$ Note that this $\operatorname{Ext}$-object is in $\mathsf{Spec}$. By Propositions 9.21 and 10.6, this is the derived mapping object in the category of right $P$-modules (with the projective model structure). Let $L,L^{\prime}$ be left $P$-modules and suppose that $L$ is $\Sigma$-cofibrant. We define $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{left}}_{P}(L,L^{\prime}):=\operatorname{Hom}^{% \mathsf{left}}_{P}(B(P,P,L),L^{\prime}).$ This $\operatorname{Ext}$-object is a pointed simplicial set because left $P$-modules are enriched only over $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$, not $\mathsf{Spec}$. Let $M,M^{\prime}$ be $P$-bimodules and suppose that $M$ is $\Sigma$-cofibrant. We define $\operatorname{Ext}^{\mathsf{bi}}_{P}(M,M^{\prime}):=\operatorname{Hom}^{% \mathsf{bi}}_{P}(B(P,P,M,P,P),M^{\prime}).$ This again is a pointed simplicial set because $P$-bimodules are also enriched only over $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$.
Definition 17.20. With $F:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ still a finite cell functor, we can now construct a natural transformation $\phi:F\to\Phi_{n}(F)$ based on the maps $\phi^{\prime\prime}_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{\tilde{% \partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})}\left(\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{% \infty}),(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge*}\right)$ of Lemma 17.19. We combine these with the cofibrant replacement map $\tilde{\partial}^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty})\to\partial^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty}),$ the truncation map $(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge*}\to(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\leq n}$ and the map from the strict mapping object for right modules to the derived mapping object $\operatorname{Map}^{\mathsf{right}}_{P}(R,R^{\prime})\to\operatorname{Ext}^{% \mathsf{right}}_{P}(R,R^{\prime})$ to get a map of the form $\phi_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Ext}_{\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega% ^{\infty})}\left(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(F\Omega^{\infty}),(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{% \leq n}\right)=\Phi_{n}(F).$ Finally, given any pointed simplicial functor $F:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$, we define $\phi_{F}:F\to\Phi_{n}(F)$ by taking the homotopy colimit over finite subcomplexes $C\subset QF$ of the maps $\phi_{C}$ above.
Definition 9.2 (Fibrations). Let $f:M\to N$ be a morphism of symmetric sequences of spectra. We say that $f$ is a fibration if each map $f_{n}:M(n)\to N(n)$ is a fibration in $\mathsf{Spec}$. If $f$ is a morphism of operads, modules, cooperads or comodules, we say that $f$ is a fibration if it is a fibration of the underlying symmetric sequences.
Definition 2.6 (Layers of the Taylor tower). The layers in the Taylor tower of $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ are the functors $D_{n}F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ given by $D_{n}F:=\operatorname*{hofib}(P_{n}F\to P_{n-1}F).$ The functor $D_{n}F$ is $n$-homogeneous, that is both $n$-excisive and $n$-reduced (i.e. $P_{n-1}(D_{n}F)\simeq*$.) Goodwillie’s classification of homogeneous functors then leads to the following proposition.
Definition 12.8. Let $F:{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{fin}}}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be a pointed simplicial functor. and let $\tilde{\partial}^{*}(QF)$ be a termwise-cofibrant replacement for $\partial^{*}(QF)$. It follows from Lemma 12.7 that the pro-symmetric sequence $\tilde{\partial}^{*}(F)$ is directly-dualizable (see Definition 11.4) and so, following 11.6 we set $\begin{split}\displaystyle\partial_{*}(F):&\displaystyle=\mathbb{D}\tilde{% \partial}^{*}(QF)\\ &\displaystyle=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{C\in\mathsf{Sub}(QF)}\operatorname{Map% }(\widetilde{\operatorname{Nat}}(CX,X^{\wedge*}),S)\end{split}$ where $\widetilde{\operatorname{Nat}}(CX,X^{\wedge*})$ denotes a cofibrant replacement of the spectrum $\operatorname{Nat}(CX,X^{\wedge*})$. Note that by Definition 6.12, the construction of $\partial_{*}(F)$ is functorial in $F$.
Definition 7.14 (Simplicial bar constructions). Let $P$ be an operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ with right module $R$ and left module $L$. Then the simplicial bar construction on $P$ with coefficients in $R$ and $L$ is a simplicial object $B_{\bullet}(R,P,L)$ in the category of symmetric sequences of spectra. The $k$-simplices are given by $B_{k}(R,P,L):=R\circ\underbrace{P\circ\dots\circ P}_{k}\circ L.$ The face and degeneracy maps are given as follows: • $d_{0}:B_{k}(R,P,L)\to B_{k-1}(R,P,L)$ by the action map $R\circ P\to R$; • $d_{i}:B_{k}(R,P,L)\to B_{k-1}(R,P,L)$ for $i=1,\dots,k-1$ by the operad composition map $P\circ P\to P$ applied to the $k$th and $k+1$th factors of $P$; • $d_{k}:B_{k}(R,P,L)\to B_{k-1}(R,P,L)$ by the action map $P\circ L\to L$; • $s_{j}:B_{k}(R,P,L)\to B_{k+1}(R,P,L)$ for $j=0,\dots,k$ by using the unit map $\mathsf{1}\to P$ to insert the $j+1$th copy of $P$. This is a standard two-sided simplicial bar construction. We now take the (termwise) geometric realization of this simplicial object to obtain what we call just the bar construction on $P$ with coefficients in $R$ and $L$: $B(R,P,L)(n):=|B_{\bullet}(R,P,L)(n)|.$ This bar construction is our model for the derivative composition product $R\circ_{P}L$ of the right and left modules $R$ and $L$, over $P$.
Definition 20.1. Let $P$ be a reduced operad in $\mathsf{Spec}$ with right and left $P$-modules $R$ and $L$ respectively. Ignoring the homotopy-theoretic consequences for the moment, let us write $\mathbb{D}X$ for $\operatorname{Map}(X,S)$. Then $\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,\mathsf{1})$ is an operad with right and left modules $\mathbb{D}B(R,P,\mathsf{1})$ and $\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,L)$ respectively. Furthermore, recall (by dualizing the maps of Proposition 7.15) that we have composition maps $\mathbb{D}B(R,P,\mathsf{1})\circ\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,L)\to\mathbb{D}B(R,P,L)$ and hence $\mathbb{D}B(R,P,\mathsf{1})\circ\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,\mathsf{1})^{k}\circ% \mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,L)\to\mathbb{D}B(R,P,L)$ for each $k$. Together these make up a map of symmetric sequences $B(\mathbb{D}B(R,P,\mathsf{1}),\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,\mathsf{1}),\mathbb{D}B% (\mathsf{1},P,L))\to\mathbb{D}B(R,P,L).$ To make this have better homotopical properties, we can compose with termwise-cofibrant replacements for the operad and modules on the left-hand side to get $\Gamma:B\left(\widetilde{\mathbb{D}B(R,P,\mathsf{1})},\widetilde{\mathbb{D}B(% \mathsf{1},P,\mathsf{1})},\widetilde{\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{1},P,L)}\right)\to% \mathbb{D}B(R,P,L).$
Definition 1.13 (Augmented simplicial objects). Let $X_{\bullet}$ be a simplicial object in a category $\mathcal{C}$. An augmentation of $X_{\bullet}$ is a map $\epsilon:X_{0}\to Y$ in $\mathcal{C}$ such that $\epsilon d_{0}=\epsilon d_{1}$. If $\mathcal{C}$ is either $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ or $\mathsf{Spec}$, then such an augmentation determines a map $\tilde{\epsilon}:|X_{\bullet}|\to Y.$ Dually, if $X^{\bullet}$ is a cosimplicial object in $\mathcal{C}$, then an augmentation of $X^{\bullet}$ is a map $\eta:Y\to X^{0}$ such that $d^{0}\eta=d^{1}\eta$. This determines a map $\tilde{\eta}:Y\to\operatorname{Tot}X^{\bullet}.$
Definition 1.2 (Spectra). Let $\mathsf{Spec}$ be the category of $S$-modules of EKMM [13] (there this category is denoted $\mathcal{M}_{S}$). This is our model for the stable homotopy category. Unlike [13], we refer to an object of $\mathsf{Spec}$ as a spectrum, rather than an $S$-module. In [13], the word ‘spectrum’ is reserved for a more fundamental notion, with an $S$-module having additional structure. We choose this different terminology to avoid clashing with modules over operads which feature heavily in this paper. We stress that whenever we write ‘spectrum’, we mean an object of $\mathsf{Spec}$, that is, an $S$-module in the sense of [13]. The category $\mathsf{Spec}$ then has the following properties: • $\mathsf{Spec}$ is closed symmetric monoidal with respect to the smash product $\wedge_{S}$ which we write just as $\wedge$. The unit for the smash product is the sphere spectrum $S$. For spectra $X,Y$, we write $\operatorname{Map}(X,Y)$ for the internal mapping object, that is spectrum of maps from $X$ to $Y$ (We avoid the usual notation $F_{S}(X,Y)$ because we often use $F$ to denote a arbitrary functor); • $\mathsf{Spec}$ is enriched, tensored and cotensored over the category $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$. For spectra $X,Y$, we write $\mathsf{Spec}(X,Y)$ for the simplicial set of maps from $X$ to $Y$, and for $K\in\mathsf{sSet}_{*},X\in\mathsf{Spec}$, we write $X\wedge K$ for the tensor object in $\mathsf{Spec}$. (In [13] only the enrichment over based topological spaces is considered. We obtain $\mathsf{Spec}(X,Y)$ by applying the singular simplicial set functor to the topological mapping object.) • There is a cofibrantly generated pointed proper simplicial monoidal model structure on $\mathsf{Spec}$ in which the generating cofibrations are given by maps $S\wedge_{\mathcal{L}}\mathbb{L}\Sigma^{\infty}_{q}|\partial\Delta[n]_{+}|\to S% \wedge_{\mathcal{L}}\mathbb{L}\Sigma^{\infty}_{q}|\Delta[n]_{+}|$ for $q,n\geq 0$. (See [13, I.4-5] for the notation here.) This model structure is described in more detail in [13, VII]. • Every object in $\mathsf{Spec}$ is fibrant in this model structure.
Definition 9.10 ($\Sigma_{n}$-cofibrations). There is a projective model structure on the category $\mathsf{Spec}^{\Sigma_{n}}$ whose objects are spectra with $\Sigma_{n}$-actions, and whose morphisms are $\Sigma_{n}$-equivariant maps of spectra. If $E$ is an object in this category, we say that $E$ is $\Sigma_{n}$-cofibrant if it is cofibrant in this projective model structure. Equivalently, this means that $E$ has the left-lifting property with respect to $\Sigma_{n}$-equivariant maps of spectra that are trivial fibrations in $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 15.9. The main result of [11] is that the Spanier-Whitehead dual of the reduced bar construction on the commutative operad is, as a symmetric sequence, equivalent to the Goodwillie derivatives of the identity functor on based spaces, that is: $\partial^{G}_{*}(I_{\mathsf{sSet}_{*}})\simeq\mathbb{D}B(\mathsf{Com}).$ On the level of symmetric sequences, this result is due to the first author and Mark Mahowald in [5]. The operad structure is constructed in [11]. Proposition 15.7, together with the homotopy invariance of the bar construction (Proposition 8.5), then implies that those derivatives of the identity are equivalent to $\mathbb{D}B(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty})).$ The cooperad $B(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}\Omega^{\infty}))$ is directly-dualizable by Lemma 11.14 and so this dual has an operad structure by Lemma 11.11. It is convenient to have notation for the operad formed by this dual. Since we know that it is equivalent to the derivatives of the identity on based spaces, we write $\partial_{*}(I):=\widetilde{\mathbb{D}B(\tilde{\partial}^{*}(\Sigma^{\infty}% \Omega^{\infty}))}.$ (For convenience we include a $\Sigma$-cofibrant replacement in this definition.) In §19 below, we give another proof that this operad is equivalent to the derivatives of the identity on based spaces that does not directly use [5]. However, our proof (indeed the main ideas of this paper) is still based on the adjunction $(\Sigma^{\infty},\Omega^{\infty})$, which was also the basis for studying the derivatives of the identity in [4], and continued in [5].
Definition 6.11 (Directly dualizable pro-spectra). The pro-spectra we deal with in this paper almost exclusively satisfy the conditions of Lemma 6.10. It is helpful to have some terminology for this case. We say that a pro-spectrum $X$ is directly-dualizable if • the indexing category for $X$ is a cofiltered poset in which every element has finitely many successors; • each spectrum $X_{j}$ is cofibrant and homotopy-finite. In this case we fix a model for the Spanier-Whitehead dual $\mathbb{D}X$ using Lemma 6.10. We define $\mathbb{D}X:=\operatorname*{hocolim}_{j\in\mathcal{J}}\operatorname{Map}(X_{j}% ,S).$ The homotopy colimit here is formed in the category $\mathsf{Spec}$. Later on in this paper, we consider the Spanier-Whitehead duals of collections of pro-spectra that have extra structure. In those cases, we form the homotopy colimit in other categories in order to retain that additional information. (See §11.)
Definition 17.18. First let $F:\mathsf{sSet}_{*}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be a finite cell functor. We define maps $\phi^{\prime}_{F}(r):=F(X)\wedge\partial^{r}(F\Omega^{\infty})\to(\Sigma^{% \infty}X)^{\wedge r}.$ These are made by combining the map $F(X)\to F\Omega^{\infty}\Sigma^{\infty}(X)$ that comes from the $(\Sigma^{\infty},\Omega^{\infty})$-adjunction with the evaluation map $F\Omega^{\infty}\Sigma^{\infty}(X)\wedge\operatorname{Nat}(F\Omega^{\infty}E,E% ^{\wedge r})\to(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge r}.$ The maps $\phi^{\prime}_{F}(r)$ are $\Sigma_{r}$-equivariant and so together define a map $\phi^{\prime}_{F}:F(X)\to\operatorname{Map}_{\mathsf{\Sigma}}\left(\partial^{*% }(F\Omega^{\infty}),(\Sigma^{\infty}X)^{\wedge*}\right).$
Definition 1.11 (Simplicial and cosimplicial objects). Simplicial and cosimplicial objects in our categories $\mathsf{sSet}_{*}$ and $\mathsf{Spec}$ play an important role in this paper. We write $\mathsf{\Delta}$ for the category whose objects are the totally ordered sets $\mathbf{n}:=\{0,\dots,n\}$ for $n\geq 0$, and whose morphisms are the order-preserving functions. A simplicial object in a category $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor $X_{\bullet}:\mathsf{\Delta}^{op}\to\mathcal{C}$, and a cosimplicial object in $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor $X^{\bullet}:\mathsf{\Delta}\to\mathcal{C}$. We refer to the object $X_{k}:=X_{\bullet}(\mathbf{k})$ or $X^{k}:=X^{\bullet}(\mathbf{k})$ as the object of $k$-simplices in $X_{\bullet}$ or $X^{\bullet}$ respectively. More explicitly, a simplicial object in $\mathcal{C}$ consists of a sequence of objects $X_{k}\in\mathcal{C}$ for $k\geq 0$ and: • face maps $d_{i}:X_{k}\to X_{k-1}$ for $i=0,\dots,k$; • degeneracy maps $s_{j}:X_{k}\to X_{k+1}$ for $j=0,\dots,k$; satisfying the ‘simplicial identities’ (see [15, I.1]). Dually, a cosimplicial object in $\mathcal{C}$ consists of objects $X^{k}\in\mathcal{C}$ for $k\geq 0$ and: • coface maps $d^{i}:X^{k}\to X^{k+1}$ for $i=0,\dots,k+1$; • codegeneracy maps $s^{j}:X^{k}\to X^{k-1}$ for $j=0,\dots,k-1$; satisfying corresponding ‘cosimplicial identities’.
Definition 2.2 ($n$-excisive functors). A homotopy functor $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ is $n$-excisive if it takes strongly cocartesian $(n+1)$- dimensional cubes in $\mathcal{C}$ to cartesian cubes in $\mathcal{D}$. See [17] for more details on this definition.
Definition 8.4 (Termwise-cofibrant operads). Let $M$ be a symmetric sequence in $\mathsf{Spec}$. We say that $M$ is termwise-cofibrant if: (1) $M(n)$ is a cofibrant spectrum for $n\geq 2$; and (2) either $M(1)$ is a cofibrant spectrum, or $M(1)\cong S$. Recall that the sphere spectrum $S$ is not cofibrant, so the alternatives in the second condition here are meaningful. It is important for us to include the case $M(1)\cong S$ to allow for reduced operads, and for the unit symmetric sequence $\mathsf{1}$.
Definition 12.5. Now let $F:{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{fin}}}\to\mathsf{Spec}$ be any pointed simplicial functor. Then there the cellular replacement $QF$ of $F$ (Definition 4.6) comes with a canonical presentation and so we can form the pro-symmetric sequence $\partial^{*}(QF)$ as in Definition 12.4. This pro-symmetric sequence comprises our models for the (Spanier-Whitehead duals of) the Goodwillie derivatives of $F$. A natural transformation $\gamma:F\to G$ induces a morphism of pro-symmetric sequences $\partial^{*}(\gamma):\partial^{*}(QG)\to\partial^{*}(QF)$ in the following way: • Recall that a degree $i$ cell $\alpha$ in the presented cell complex $QF$ corresponds to a commutative diagram of the form $\diagram\node{I_{0}\wedge\mathsf{Spec}(K,-)}\arrow{e}\arrow{s}\node{(QF)_{i-1}% }\arrow{s}\\ \node{I_{1}\wedge\mathsf{Spec}(K,-)}\arrow{e}\node{F}$ Composing this with the diagram $\diagram\node{(QF)_{i-1}}\arrow{e,t}{Q\gamma}\arrow{s}\node{(QG)_{i-1}}\arrow{% s}\\ \node{F}\arrow{e,t}{\gamma}\node{G}$ induced by $\gamma$, we obtain a corresponding cell $\gamma_{\alpha}$ of degree $i$ in $QG$. • Now let $C$ be a finite subcomplex of $QF$. Then the cells $\gamma_{\alpha}$ for $\alpha\in C$ form a finite subcomplex $C^{\prime}$ of $QG$ and $Q(\gamma)$ restricts to a map $\gamma_{C}:C\to C^{\prime}.$ (Note that $C^{\prime}$ can have fewer cells than $C$, for example if $G=*$.) • We then define the map $\partial^{n}(\gamma)_{C}:\operatorname{Nat}(C^{\prime}(X),X^{\wedge n})\to% \operatorname{Nat}(CX,X^{\wedge n})$ induced by $\gamma:C\to C^{\prime}$ coming from the previous construction. Together these make up a morphism of pro-objects $\partial^{n}(QG)\to\partial^{n}(QF)$. It is easy to see that these maps are $\Sigma_{n}$-equivariant and form a morphism of pro-symmetric sequences as claimed. This construction makes $\partial^{*}(Q-)$ into a contravariant functor from $[{\mathsf{Spec}^{\mathsf{fin}}},\mathsf{Spec}]$ to the category of pro-symmetric sequences in $\mathsf{Spec}$.
Definition 4.7 (Kan extension). In order to describe the chain rule we have to be able to compose the functors we are working with. We therefore extend an object $F\in[\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}},\mathcal{D}]$ to a pointed simplicial functors $LF:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ by enriched left Kan extension. Explicitly, for $X\in\mathcal{C}$, we define $LF(X):=\operatorname*{colim}\left(\bigvee_{K,K^{\prime}\in\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf% {fin}}}F(K)\wedge\mathcal{C}(K,K^{\prime})\wedge\mathcal{C}(K^{\prime},X)% \rightrightarrows\bigvee_{K\in\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}}F(K)\wedge\mathcal{C}% (K,X)\right).$ One map in this coequalizer is given by the composition map $\mathcal{C}(K,K^{\prime})\wedge\mathcal{C}(K^{\prime},X)\to\mathcal{C}(K,X)$ and the other by $FK\wedge\mathcal{C}(K,K^{\prime})\to FK\wedge\mathcal{D}(FK,FK^{\prime})\to FK% ^{\prime}.$ Equivalently, this is an (enriched) coend (in the sense of MacLane [35]). The Kan extension $LF$ satisfies the following universal property. If we have any pointed simplicial functor $H:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ then there is a 1-1 correspondence between natural transformations $F\to H|_{\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}}$, i.e. from $F$ to the restriction of $H$ to $\mathcal{C}^{\mathsf{fin}}$, and natural transformations $LF\to H$.
